---

## Sample Output

The assistant generates:

- Executive Summary
- Knowledge Drift Report
- Confidence Assessment

Each detected drift includes:

- Area
- Confluence Evidence
- Azure DevOps Evidence
- Impact

---

## Design Principles

### Compare, Don't Summarize

The objective is to identify knowledge drift rather than summarize documents.

### Structured Inputs

Both Confluence and Azure DevOps artifacts are converted into structured representations before being sent to the LLM.

### Deterministic Parsing

HTML and Excel parsing are handled entirely using deterministic Python code.

The LLM is responsible only for semantic reasoning.

### Modular Architecture

The project separates:

- Parsing
- Prompt construction
- AI communication
- UI

making the solution easy to maintain and extend.

---

## Current Limitations

- Single Confluence page
- Single Azure DevOps export 
- Single business feature has to be of all stories for only one feature
- No multi-feature hierarchy
- No evidence highlighting
- No severity scoring
- No semantic retrieval
- No document update recommendations

---

## Future Vision

The long-term goal is to evolve this prototype into an enterprise Knowledge Drift Detection platform capable of comparing multiple knowledge sources, including:

- Confluence
- Azure DevOps
- User Guides
- FAQs
- Release Notes
- SharePoint documentation

using semantic retrieval and Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) to identify outdated or inconsistent knowledge across the enterprise.

---

## Why this project?

This project explores how Generative AI can help Product Managers ensure that implementation and documentation remain aligned throughout the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC).

Rather than replacing documentation processes, the assistant reduces the effort required to identify documentation drift before release.